# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1937-detroit-tigers-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1894-in-baseball] The following are the baseball events of the year 1894 throughout the world.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The **1900 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' first in the American League, which received recognition as a major league one year later in 1901.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in fourth place out of eight teams with a record of 71–67, 12+1⁄2 games behind Charles Comiskey's Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Outfielder Dick Harley led the team with a .325 batting average, 77 runs scored, and 47 stolen bases.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Sport McAllister led in slugging percentage (.383), and Frank Dillon led in extra-base hits (30).
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller led the team with a 19–9 win-loss record for a .679 win percentage.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Jack Cronin led in innings pitched (372) and strikeouts (121).
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1900-detroit-tigers-season] Burns and George Stallings had spent large sums of money for "releases of star players" and had paid "major league salaries" to the majority of the players.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The **1901 Detroit Tigers season** was the Tigers' 2nd season in Major League Baseball.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team was a charter member of the American League, which was originally formed as the minor-league Western League, of which it had also been a charter member.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers finished in third place with a record or 74–61, 8+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Most of Detroit's home games were played at Bennett Park, with Sunday games played at Burns Park due to Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Roscoe Miller (23–13) led the team in wins and was the Tigers' first 20-game winner.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] His performance headlined a strong pitching staff that had the third lowest ERA (3.30) in the American League.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Joe Yeager had an ERA of 2.61, for the second best Adjusted ERA+ in the AL, behind Cy Young.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The offense was not as strong however, scoring 741 runs – fifth among the eight teams in the league.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The team's best hitters were shortstop Kid Elberfeld (.308 average) and center fielder Jimmy Barrett (.293 average; 110 runs).
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had played their games at Bennett Park since 1896, but the graduation to a major league meant that there would now be games scheduled on Sundays, which was forbidden by Detroit's blue laws.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] In order to avoid running afoul of this stricture, owner James D.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Burns built a ballpark on his own property in Springwells Township, Michigan just outside the Detroit city limits.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Named Burns Park, the Tigers would play their Sunday home games there for the 1901 and 1902 seasons.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] During the 1901 season, Detroit attracted 259,430 fans at home and 238,100 on the road, for a total of 447,428.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1901-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit ranked third behind Chicago and Boston in overall attendance.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] 1902 was the second year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the newly formed American League.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 58–77 (.385), 30½ games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The 1902 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 657 runs to 566.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 189,469, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] Detroit's blue laws prevented the Tigers from playing baseball at Bennett Park on Sundays.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1902-detroit-tigers-season] As a result, the Tigers played their Sunday home games for the season at Burns Park; a stadium constructed by owner James D.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] 1903 was the third year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the still-new American League.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in fifth place with a record or 65–71 (.478), 25 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The 1903 Tigers outscored their opponents 567 to 539.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1903-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 224,523, sixth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] 1904 was the fourth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in seventh place with a record of 62–90 (.408), 32 games behind the Boston Americans.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] They played ten tie games, which is the major league record.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The 1904 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 627 to 505.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 177,796, seventh out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1904-detroit-tigers-season] In the year before Ty Cobb's arrival, pitcher George Mullin had a higher batting average than any of the team's regulars at .290.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] 1905 was the fifth year for the **Detroit Tigers** in the American League.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished in third place with a record of 79–74 (.516), 151⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The 1905 Tigers posted a run differential of -97, the lowest ever by a team with a winning record, breaking the previous record of -81 held by the 1882 Detroit Wolverines; the Tigers lost 48 games by 3 or more runs.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The 1905 Tigers were outscored by their opponents 602 to 512, the largest negative run differential ever for a Major League team with a winning record.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1905-detroit-tigers-season] The team's attendance at Bennett Park was 193,384, eighth out of the eight teams in the AL.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The **1937 Detroit Tigers** finished in second place in the American League with a record of 89–65.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The team finished 13 games behind the New York Yankees.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Their winning percentage of .578 ranks as the 15th best season in Detroit Tigers history.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The strength of the 1937 Tigers was hitting.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers had scored 900 or more runs each season from 1934 to 1937.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The 1937 total of 935 runs is the second highest in franchise history, trailing only the 1934 Tigers team that scored 958 runs.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The 1937 Tigers led the major leagues with a .292 batting average—nine points higher than the Yankees.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The 1937 Tigers also had power, belting twice as many home runs (150 to 74) as the 1934 team.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Second baseman Charlie Gehringer won both the American League batting title and the AL Most Valuable Player Award.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] First baseman Hank Greenberg led the major leagues with 183 RBIs—still the third highest single season total in major league history.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Rookie catcher Rudy York did not make it into the starting lineup until early August and promptly broke the AL record with 18 home runs in the month.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] York finished as the AL leader in at bats per home run (10.7) and with the third highest slugging percentage (.651) in the major leagues.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] While the team had the bats, it lacked the pitching to compete with the Yankees.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In contrast to its league-best batting average, the Tigers pitching staff had an ERA of 4.87—ranking seventh among the eight American League teams.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Elden Auker (17–9; 3.88) was the only pitcher on the staff with an ERA below 4.00.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Former ace Schoolboy Rowe was suspended at the beginning of the year for poor conditioning, pitched only 31.1 innings for the year, and compiled a staggering 7.59 ERA.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The team continued to have strong support from Detroit fans, finishing the 1937 season with a team record 1,072,276 fans attending the team's home games at Briggs Stadium.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The only American League team to draw more fans up to that time was the 1930 Yankees' team that drew 1,169,230.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The 1937 season began with **Mickey Cochrane** as the team's player/manager.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] However, Cochrane's playing career came to a sudden end on May 25, 1937.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] After hitting a home run in the third inning, Cochrane was hit in the head by a pitch from Yankees pitcher Bump Hadley when he next came to bat.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Hospitalized for seven days, the injury nearly killed him.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Ordered by doctors not to play baseball again (he was just 34 years old), Cochrane returned to the dugout but never played again.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Backup catcher Ray Hayworth had his arm broken by a pitched ball shortly after Cochrane's injury, and Birdie Tebbetts took over the catching duties for most of June and July.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] At the beginning of August, rookie **Rudy York** took over as the team's catcher and set the league on fire with his home run hitting.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In August 1937, his first full month in the major leagues, York broke Babe Ruth's major league record for most home runs in a single month, hitting 18 home runs (and 44 RBIs).
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] For the year, York hit .307 with a .651 slugging percentage, 35 home runs, and 103 RBIs.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Defensively, York was a liability at catcher, leading the AL in passed balls in 1937 despite playing only two months.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In 1940, the Tigers persuaded Hank Greenberg to move to left field, allowing York to take over at first base.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] York was among the American League leaders in home runs for 11 consecutive seasons from 1937 to 1947, and his .503 slugging percentage as a Tiger ranks #4 in franchise history.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The Detroit infield remained intact for five years from 1933 through 1937: Hank Greenberg at first, Charlie Gehringer at second, Billy Rogell at shortstop, and Marv Owen at third.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] They were a solid group both at the bat and defensively.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In 1937, Greenberg led the AL in putouts with 1477, and Gehringer, Rogell, and Owen all led the league in fielding percentage at their position.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Shortstop **Billy Rogell** led all AL shortstops in fielding percentage each year from 1935 to 1937, and in 1937 he hit .276 and scored 85 runs.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Rogell and Gehringer played over 1,000 games together as the Tigers' double play combination.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Rogell's fiery demeanor was a stark contrast to the calm, quiet demeanor of Gehringer.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] After retiring from baseball, Rogell served on the Detroit City Council from 1942 to 1980 .
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] He was chairman of the city planning committee that built Detroit Metropolitan Airport, and the road entering the airport from the north, Merriman Road, changes its name to William G.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In the outfield, the Tigers had Gee Walker, Pete Fox, and Jo-Jo White.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Right fielder **Pete Fox** was a mainstay in the Detroit outfield for eight seasons (1933–1940).
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] He played on three AL pennant champion teams, and he was the Tigers' leading hitter in the 1935 World Series.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Though a native of Indiana, Detroit became his adopted home, and he died there in 1966.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In 1937, Fox hit .331 and was among the league leaders with 149 singles (3rd), 208 hits (6th), 116 runs scored (8th), and 12 stolen bases (10th).
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Center fielder **Jo-Jo White** played in the Tigers' outfield from 1932 to 1938.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] He hit .313 in 1934, but his average fell off after that year.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In 1937, Jo-Jo hit .246 and played only 94 games.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] White's real first name was Joyner, but he was called "Jo-Jo" because of the way he pronounced his native state of Georgia.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Rookie Chet Laabs also played 62 games in the outfield for the 1937 Tigers.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Labs hit .240 with a .434 slugging percentage.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] In 1938, Laabs struck out five times in one game against Bob Feller, helping Feller set the all-time record with 18 strikeouts in a nine-inning game.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Laabs later hit 27 home runs with 99 RBIs for the 1943 St.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Hall of Famer Goose Goslin also played in 39 games, but his batting average fell to .238 with 43 hits and 35 RBIs.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The Tigers released Goslin on October 3, 1937, and Goslin later recounted (in "*The Glory of Their Times*") that he received a call from his old boss, Clark Griffith, asking him if he'd be interested in ending his career back where it began in Washington.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Goslin jumped at the opportunity and batted .158 in 38 games for the Senators in the 1938 season.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] The Senators played in only three World Series in their history (1924, 1925, and 1933), and Goslin played for the Senators in every game of those Series.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] After three consecutive 20+ win seasons, **Tommy Bridges** dropped to a 15–12 season with a 4.07 ERA.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] He continued, however, to be among the league leaders with 138 strikeouts (5th in the AL).
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Bridges played in four World Series and six All-Star Games with the Tigers.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] One of the hardest throwers of the 1930s, Bridges was among the AL leaders in strikeouts 12 times and led the league in strikeouts in 1935 and 1936.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Rookie **Boots Poffenberger** was called up to the Tigers mid-season and went 10–5.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] His won-loss percentage of .667 in 1937 was seventh best in the AL.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Boots was only 21 years old when he debuted with the Tigers, and his career spun out of control within two years.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Stories about Poffenberger's late night drinking and poor training practices caused him to fall out of favor with the team.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] After a night of heavy drinking while on the road in 1937, Poffenberger called room service and said, "I'll have the breakfast of champions." When asked if he wanted cereal, Poffenberge replied, "Hell, no.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Pitcher **"Whistling Jake" Wade** also had his most productive season in 1937, posting career highs in wins (7), starts (25), complete games (7), strikeouts (69) and innings pitched (165-1/3).
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Wade pitched a one-hit shutout in the last game of the 1937 regular season, preventing Cleveland pitcher Johnny Allen from tying the AL record of 16 straight wins.
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] However, Wade struggled with control and was among the AL leaders in 1937 with 107 walks allowed (7th) and five wild pitches (8th).
[src:1937-detroit-tigers-season/1937-detroit-tigers-season] Wade was nicknamed "Whistling Jake" not for his fastball but because of his tendency to whistle whenever he was nervous.
